# Rules
<!-- Compiled 2026-03-22 12:35 by carl-compiler.py -->

## Critical

- Every new CARL rule must have a testable failure condition. If you cannot describe a scenario where the rule would catch a violation, the rule is too vague to create.
- No rule may weaken, override, or contradict a CRITICAL-priority rule without Oliver's explicit approval in the current session. CRITICAL rules are constitutional — they outrank everything except Oliver's direct instruction.
- Every rule must trace to one of: (a) a correction from Oliver, (b) an experiment result with data, (c) a safety requirement. No rules from intuition, speculation, or "best practice" without evidence. If the source is unclear, ask before creating.
- CREDIT APPROVAL GATE: Before executing any research or list-build task, estimate the total credit cost. If estimated cost exceeds 50 credits, STOP and present the estimate to Oliver. Log actual credits used after completion in domain/pipeline/startup-brief.md.
- UNIVERSAL PROSPECT RESEARCH: Before ANY prospect-facing activity (email, call, demo, LinkedIn), run this research sequence: (1) brain/prospects/[Name].md — existing notes, angles tried, outcomes. (2) Apollo MCP (apollo_contacts_search) — contact data, Activities tab for prior calls/transcripts/touchpoints. (3) Fireflies (fireflies_search) — prior call transcripts (critical for follow-ups and demo prep). (4) Web research — LinkedIn profile (posts, activity, job changes, mutual connections), company website, news. (5) NotebookLM — ingest research into ICP Signals notebook (bf84ba08) for general prospects; ALSO add to Demo Prep notebook (6bdf40a0) if demo is booked. For demo prep specifically: also run deep research mode (--mode deep --no-wait --import-all) and wait for completion before querying. The goal: find at least one specific, referenceable detail about this person before any output.
- CHANNEL COLLISION BLOCK: If a LinkedIn message was sent to a prospect within the last 24 hours, do NOT send an email. Check brain/prospects/[Name].md for the last LinkedIn touch timestamp before any email draft. The reverse also applies. Minimum 24-hour gap between channels. Violation = tag [CHANNEL_COLLISION] in daily notes.
- TRUTH & VERIFICATION: No success claims without evidence. Show tool output (IDs, paths, API responses) for every state-changing action. Cite sources for every data claim. No silent failures — report immediately. Never fabricate. Full verification protocols, banned success phrases, and mutation logging rules: .claude/truth-protocol.md. This rule and that file are the single source of truth — no other file repeats these constraints.
- BRUTAL HONESTY: On EVERY output and EVERY recommendation, proactively surface what's weak, what's risky, and what you're unsure about. Don't wait to be asked. Don't bury concerns in politeness. If you think a task is wrong-priority, wrong-timing, or over-engineered — say so BEFORE executing, not after. Silence on concerns = failure. This applies to every action, not just when pushed.
- Before ANY outbound activity (email, call prep, demo prep, proposal, follow-up), read brain/emails/PATTERNS.md. Check: (1) What angle/approach works best for this persona? (2) What tone gets results at this deal stage? (3) What framework converts for this scenario? (4) What approaches have FAILED for similar prospects? (5) What's the confidence level for each recommendation? Apply insights. If no data exists, use best judgment and tag carefully for future learning.
- Before ANY outbound activity (email, call prep, demo prep, proposal, follow-up), read brain/emails/PATTERNS.md. Check: (1) What angle/approach works best for this persona? (2) What tone gets results at this deal stage? (3) What framework converts for this scenario? (4) What approaches have FAILED for similar prospects? (5) What's the confidence level for each recommendation? Apply insights. If no data exists, use best judgment and tag carefully for future learning.
- When choosing an approach for any follow-up touch, NEVER repeat the same angle that failed. Check the prospect's sequence history in brain/prospects/[Name].md. If Touch 1 used "case-study" and got no reply, Touch 2 must use a different angle. If a demo thread fell flat, don't lead with it next time. Repetition = ghosted. This is Loop's most important rule.
- When choosing an approach for any follow-up touch, NEVER repeat the same angle that failed. Check the prospect's sequence history in brain/prospects/[Name].md. If Touch 1 used "case-study" and got no reply, Touch 2 must use a different angle. If a demo thread fell flat, don't lead with it next time. Repetition = ghosted. This is Loop's most important rule.
- Never fabricate outcome data. If unknown whether an email got a reply, set outcome to "pending" and check Gmail. If Gmail returns nothing AND next_touch passed, set "no-reply". Bad data poisons the learning loop. Variables with <3 data points = [INSUFFICIENT], never present as guidance.
- Never fabricate outcome data. If unknown whether an email got a reply, set outcome to "pending" and check Gmail. If Gmail returns nothing AND next_touch passed, set "no-reply". Bad data poisons the learning loop. Variables with <3 data points = [INSUFFICIENT], never present as guidance.
- When presenting pattern insights, ALWAYS cite data: "Agency owners respond 40% to case-study angles (8/20 emails, [EMERGING])." Never present raw percentages without sample size and confidence level. If Oliver asks "what works?" and the answer is [HYPOTHESIS], say so.
- When presenting pattern insights, ALWAYS cite data: "Agency owners respond 40% to case-study angles (8/20 emails, [EMERGING])." Never present raw percentages without sample size and confidence level. If Oliver asks "what works?" and the answer is [HYPOTHESIS], say so.
- If a prospect note has stage >= demo-scheduled and pipedrive_deal_id is empty, flag as CRITICAL at session startup. Do not draft follow-ups or proposals for this prospect until the deal ID is populated. This ensures CRM-to-brain bidirectional sync.
