- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 1 (PROSPECT WORK): Trigger: any prospect note was read, email drafted, LinkedIn message sent, or call logged this session. Compound: (a) reply rates by angle — recalculate from brain/prospects/ and update PATTERNS.md Angle Performance table. (b) Touch sequence performance — which touch position (1st, 2nd, 3rd+) gets the most replies. (c) Stage conversion — track which activities precede stage changes. (d) Ghosted candidate detection — any prospect with 3+ consecutive no-reply outcomes → auto-add #ghosted-candidate tag to brain note, surface: "PASSIVE: [prospect] tagged #ghosted-candidate — [N] consecutive no-replies." (e) Angle underperformance — any angle with 5+ attempts and <20% reply rate → tag UNDERPERFORMING in PATTERNS.md, surface: "PASSIVE: [angle] underperforming — [X]% over [N] attempts." (f) Segment outperformance — if any ICP segment (agency, DTC, PE rollup, franchise, solo consultant) reply rate is 2x+ the monthly average → note in PATTERNS.md Cross-Deal Insights, surface: "PASSIVE: [segment] outperforming — [X]% vs [Y]% average." Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Prospect Work".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 1 (PROSPECT WORK): Trigger: any prospect note was read, email drafted, LinkedIn message sent, or call logged this session. Compound: (a) reply rates by angle — recalculate from brain/prospects/ and update PATTERNS.md Angle Performance table. (b) Touch sequence performance — which touch position (1st, 2nd, 3rd+) gets the most replies. (c) Stage conversion — track which activities precede stage changes. (d) Ghosted candidate detection — any prospect with 3+ consecutive no-reply outcomes → auto-add #ghosted-candidate tag to brain note, surface: "PASSIVE: [prospect] tagged #ghosted-candidate — [N] consecutive no-replies." (e) Angle underperformance — any angle with 5+ attempts and <20% reply rate → tag UNDERPERFORMING in PATTERNS.md, surface: "PASSIVE: [angle] underperforming — [X]% over [N] attempts." (f) Segment outperformance — if any ICP segment (agency, DTC, PE rollup, franchise, solo consultant) reply rate is 2x+ the monthly average → note in PATTERNS.md Cross-Deal Insights, surface: "PASSIVE: [segment] outperforming — [X]% vs [Y]% average." Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Prospect Work".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 2 (RULE CHANGES): Trigger: any CARL rule was added, merged, deleted, or modified this session. Compound: (a) total behavioral rule count trend — log current count per domain to PATTERNS.md, flag if behavioral total crosses 100 (ceiling per LOOP_RULE_53) or any single domain crosses 70. Exclude .carl/commands and .carl/example-custom-domain from count. (b) Domain distribution — track % of behavioral rules per domain, flag if any domain holds >50% of total behavioral rules. (c) Conflict rate — track how many new rules triggered a conflict check (per LOOP_RULE_59) and how many conflicts were found. (d) Merge success rate — when rules are merged, track whether the merged rule fires as often as the originals combined. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Rule Changes".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 2 (RULE CHANGES): Trigger: any CARL rule was added, merged, deleted, or modified this session. Compound: (a) total behavioral rule count trend — log current count per domain to PATTERNS.md, flag if behavioral total crosses 100 (ceiling per LOOP_RULE_53) or any single domain crosses 70. Exclude .carl/commands and .carl/example-custom-domain from count. (b) Domain distribution — track % of behavioral rules per domain, flag if any domain holds >50% of total behavioral rules. (c) Conflict rate — track how many new rules triggered a conflict check (per LOOP_RULE_59) and how many conflicts were found. (d) Merge success rate — when rules are merged, track whether the merged rule fires as often as the originals combined. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Rule Changes".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 3 (LESSONS): Trigger: any lesson was added, promoted, graduated, or had its provisional counter decremented this session. Compound: (a) Provisional counter trends — average sessions-to-confirmation, flag lessons stuck at same counter for 5+ sessions. (b) Lesson promotion rate — % of provisional lessons that reach [CONFIRMED] vs those that get rewritten or killed. (c) Domain generation — which categories (LEADS, DRAFTING, PROCESS, CRM, etc.) are generating the most new lessons this month, flag if one category generates 3x+ the average. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Lessons".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 3 (LESSONS): Trigger: any lesson was added, promoted, graduated, or had its provisional counter decremented this session. Compound: (a) Provisional counter trends — average sessions-to-confirmation, flag lessons stuck at same counter for 5+ sessions. (b) Lesson promotion rate — % of provisional lessons that reach [CONFIRMED] vs those that get rewritten or killed. (c) Domain generation — which categories (LEADS, DRAFTING, PROCESS, CRM, etc.) are generating the most new lessons this month, flag if one category generates 3x+ the average. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Lessons".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 4 (HEALTH AUDIT): Trigger: step 6 (health audit) ran this session. Compound: (a) Health score over time — log pass rates by category (files, vault, MCPs, credits, process, data, learning) to PATTERNS.md, track 5-session rolling average per category. (b) Consistent underscoring — flag any category scoring below 80% pass rate for 3+ consecutive sessions. (c) MCP reliability — track which MCPs fail most often, flag any MCP down 2+ sessions in a row. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Health Audit".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 4 (HEALTH AUDIT): Trigger: step 6 (health audit) ran this session. Compound: (a) Health score over time — log pass rates by category (files, vault, MCPs, credits, process, data, learning) to PATTERNS.md, track 5-session rolling average per category. (b) Consistent underscoring — flag any category scoring below 80% pass rate for 3+ consecutive sessions. (c) MCP reliability — track which MCPs fail most often, flag any MCP down 2+ sessions in a row. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Health Audit".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 5 (WRAP COMPLIANCE): Trigger: every session, always runs. Compound: (a) Step skip tracking — log which wrap-up steps (0.5, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 9.5, 10) ran vs skipped this session. (b) Internal vs external catch — track whether skips were caught by the agent (self-corrected) or by Oliver (external correction). Flag: "BRAIN ALERT: Step [N] skipped 2+ sessions in a row — investigate root cause." (c) Skip pattern detection — if the same step is skipped in 3+ of the last 5 sessions, surface as systemic issue. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Wrap Compliance".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 5 (WRAP COMPLIANCE): Trigger: every session, always runs. Compound: (a) Step skip tracking — log which wrap-up steps (0.5, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 9.5, 10) ran vs skipped this session. (b) Internal vs external catch — track whether skips were caught by the agent (self-corrected) or by Oliver (external correction). Flag: "BRAIN ALERT: Step [N] skipped 2+ sessions in a row — investigate root cause." (c) Skip pattern detection — if the same step is skipped in 3+ of the last 5 sessions, surface as systemic issue. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: Wrap Compliance".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 6 (SYSTEM CHANGES): Trigger: any files reorganized, paths updated, folder structure modified, or scripts changed this session. Compound: (a) Path integrity — after any file move/rename, verify all references to that path in CLAUDE.md, SKILL.md, loop-state.md, and lessons.md still resolve. Flag broken references as "BRAIN ALERT: [file] references stale path [old_path]." (b) File reference accuracy — count how many files are referenced in loop-state.md vs actually exist on disk, flag drift >10%. (c) Structural drift — track folder structure changes over time, flag if active/ subdirectory count changes by >30% in a single session. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: System Changes".
- PASSIVE_PATTERN_RULE — CATEGORY 6 (SYSTEM CHANGES): Trigger: any files reorganized, paths updated, folder structure modified, or scripts changed this session. Compound: (a) Path integrity — after any file move/rename, verify all references to that path in CLAUDE.md, SKILL.md, loop-state.md, and lessons.md still resolve. Flag broken references as "BRAIN ALERT: [file] references stale path [old_path]." (b) File reference accuracy — count how many files are referenced in loop-state.md vs actually exist on disk, flag drift >10%. (c) Structural drift — track folder structure changes over time, flag if active/ subdirectory count changes by >30% in a single session. Write findings to PATTERNS.md under "## Passive: System Changes".
- WEEKLY_DIGEST_RULE: On the FIRST session of each week (Monday, or first session if Monday was skipped), BEFORE any other startup output, generate a 10-line weekly brief from brain/prospects/, brain/emails/PATTERNS.md, and Pipedrive data: (1) Total touches sent last 7 days (email + call + LinkedIn). (2) Reply rate last 7 days vs prior 7 days (up/down arrow + delta). (3) Top performing angle this week (highest reply rate, min 3 sends). (4) Worst performing angle this week (lowest reply rate, min 3 sends). (5) Pipeline movement — deal stage changes this week (who moved where). (6) Most overdue item — single most urgent prospect/task past due. Format as a compact block: "📊 WEEKLY DIGEST [date range]\n1. Touches: [N] (email [N], call [N], LinkedIn [N])\n2. Reply rate: [X]% (↑/↓ [delta]% vs prior week)\n3. Best angle: [angle] — [X]% ([N] sends)\n4. Worst angle: [angle] — [X]% ([N] sends)\n5. Pipeline: [summary of stage changes]\n6. Most overdue: [prospect] — [N] days past due\n---" This displays AFTER BRAIN ALERTs but BEFORE the regular session status block. If insufficient data for any line, show "[insufficient data]" — never skip the line.
- WEEKLY_DIGEST_RULE: On the FIRST session of each week (Monday, or first session if Monday was skipped), BEFORE any other startup output, generate a 10-line weekly brief from brain/prospects/, brain/emails/PATTERNS.md, and Pipedrive data: (1) Total touches sent last 7 days (email + call + LinkedIn). (2) Reply rate last 7 days vs prior 7 days (up/down arrow + delta). (3) Top performing angle this week (highest reply rate, min 3 sends). (4) Worst performing angle this week (lowest reply rate, min 3 sends). (5) Pipeline movement — deal stage changes this week (who moved where). (6) Most overdue item — single most urgent prospect/task past due. Format as a compact block: "📊 WEEKLY DIGEST [date range]\n1. Touches: [N] (email [N], call [N], LinkedIn [N])\n2. Reply rate: [X]% (↑/↓ [delta]% vs prior week)\n3. Best angle: [angle] — [X]% ([N] sends)\n4. Worst angle: [angle] — [X]% ([N] sends)\n5. Pipeline: [summary of stage changes]\n6. Most overdue: [prospect] — [N] days past due\n---" This displays AFTER BRAIN ALERTs but BEFORE the regular session status block. If insufficient data for any line, show "[insufficient data]" — never skip the line.
- FOLLOW-UP EXIT CONDITION: Stop following up on a prospect when ANY of these conditions are met: (1) 5 consecutive no-replies across different angles — log break-up email sent with date, (2) prospect says "not interested" or equivalent explicit rejection — log rejection reason, (3) deal marked closed-lost in Pipedrive — no further touches without restart signal from Oliver. After exit: update prospect file stage to closed-lost or dormant, remove from Follow-Up Tracker, log final disposition in brain/prospects/[Name].md. Re-engagement only if prospect initiates contact or Oliver explicitly reactivates.
- Reply classification: positive-reply (interested, asked question, agreed to next step), negative-reply (not interested, unsubscribe, wrong person), meeting-booked (calendar confirmed), deal-advanced (moved to next pipeline stage), objection-raised (specific objection surfaced), referral-given (referred to someone else), ghosted (3+ touches, zero engagement). Each classification feeds different pattern tables.
- Reply classification: positive-reply (interested, asked question, agreed to next step), negative-reply (not interested, unsubscribe, wrong person), meeting-booked (calendar confirmed), deal-advanced (moved to next pipeline stage), objection-raised (specific objection surfaced), referral-given (referred to someone else), ghosted (3+ touches, zero engagement). Each classification feeds different pattern tables.
- At session wrap-up, if ANY prospect interaction happened, scan ALL prospect notes in brain/prospects/ and update brain/emails/PATTERNS.md tables. Recalculate reply rates, conversion rates, confidence levels. Add new negative patterns. Update cadence rules if data suggests different timing. Surface "what changed" — newly proven patterns, newly failing angles, confidence level changes.
- At session wrap-up, if ANY prospect interaction happened, scan ALL prospect notes in brain/prospects/ and update brain/emails/PATTERNS.md tables. Recalculate reply rates, conversion rates, confidence levels. Add new negative patterns. Update cadence rules if data suggests different timing. Surface "what changed" — newly proven patterns, newly failing angles, confidence level changes.

## Normal

- AGENT TYPES & SCOPE: Five agent types with defined boundaries: (1) RESEARCH AGENT — external data sources, web search. Input: target+context. Output: structured research note. Cannot: draft, update CRM, make strategy calls. (2) DRAFT AGENT — written outputs (emails, scripts, messages, proposals). Input: research note + patterns + framework + history. Output: formatted draft. Cannot: research, update CRM, approve own output. (3) CRM AGENT — CRM reads/writes, deal stages, activities, notes, contacts. Input: action+outcome. Output: confirmed CRM state. Cannot: draft, research. (4) AUDIT AGENT — quality scoring, gate verification, pattern analysis, health checks. Input: any output. Output: score+gaps+recommendations. Cannot: fix what it finds (separation of concerns). Must be independent — never audits own work. (5) ORCHESTRATOR — main session. Routes inputs, spawns agents, handles user interaction. Never does work a specialized agent should do. Domain-specific agent tools: domain/carl/agents.
- AGENT CONTRACTS: Input — every agent receives a structured brief: task_type, target_name+context, file paths to read, specific deliverable expected, quality rubric reference. Subagents also get: note template path, quality rules path, post-validation instructions. Output — every agent returns: deliverable, self_score (per quality-rubrics.md), confidence level, files_modified list, flags (anything unexpected). Orchestrator reviews flags before presenting.
- AGENT PIPELINES: Research→Draft: research output becomes draft input. Draft MUST NOT re-research — trusts the note. Insufficient research → draft returns "INSUFFICIENT RESEARCH: [what's missing]" to orchestrator. Draft→Audit: audit scores independently. Score < 7 → back to draft with feedback. Max 2 revision cycles — still < 7 after 2 → escalate with both draft and audit notes. Batch: 3+ independent tasks → orchestrator spawns parallel agents, collects results, presents summary. CRM agent handles all writes in batch after others complete.
- Use specialized agents when: (1) task has clear separation of research/draft/CRM/audit, (2) 3+ independent items can parallelize, (3) audit independence matters (wrap-up scoring), (4) CRM batch operations. Do NOT spawn agents for: single quick lookups, user-directed edits, conversational exchanges, tasks requiring real-time user feedback loops.
- AGENT COST CONTROL: Research agents hitting paid tools must batch queries. CRM agent uses batch execution. Never spawn 3 research agents each calling paid APIs — spawn 1 that batches all lookups. Maximum 5 subagents per session unless approved. Track agents_spawned_this_session. At 5 → warn: "Agent budget reached. Approve more?"
- HARD BOUNDARY: Research Agent prompt MUST NOT include instructions to draft, update CRM, or approve output. If research agent returns a draft → reject and re-spawn.
- HARD BOUNDARY: Draft Agent prompt MUST include research output as input. Draft agent MUST NOT have paid tool access. Needs more research → returns "INSUFFICIENT RESEARCH: [what's missing]".
- HARD BOUNDARY: Audit Agent MUST NOT receive draft agent's self-score. Scores independently. 2+ point divergence → flag for user.
- ENFORCEMENT LOG: Every subagent spawn logged with: agent_type, task_summary, input_contract, output_contract, boundary_violations detected. Log to brain/system-patterns.md Agent Execution Log section.
- Bullet points only - no prose paragraphs
- Maximum 5 items per response unless more explicitly needed
- Skip explanations unless directly asked
- Use code snippets over descriptions when applicable
- *carl - Enter CARL Help Mode as a friendly guide for understanding and using CARL
- CARL = Context Augmentation & Reinforcement Layer - NOT "Context Aware Rule Loader" or any other expansion
- Introduce: "I'm in CARL Help Mode. I can explain how CARL works, help you set up domains/rules, or show your current configuration."
- Offer quick options: (1) Explain how CARL works (2) Help me create a domain (3) Show my current setup (4) List available commands
- For management tasks (create/edit/toggle domains), invoke /carl skill to handle file operations
- MUST READ ~/.claude/skills/carl-help/CARL-OVERVIEW.md before answering questions about CARL - do not guess or hallucinate
- File structure: .carl/manifest (no extension), .carl/global, .carl/commands, .carl/context, .carl/{domain} - NO .carl extensions on files
- Key concepts: domains load JIT via recall keywords, manifest controls state, star-commands (*xyz) are explicit triggers, GLOBAL always loads
- Syntax essentials: filenames are lowercase with NO extension, prefixes UPPERCASE, format is DOMAIN_RULE_N=text, manifest uses STATE/RECALL/EXCLUDE/ALWAYS_ON
- Before any call, check brain/prospects/ for existing notes on the contact. Then check Apollo MCP (apollo_contacts_search) for contact data, title, company, stage, and any prior touchpoints. Pull the prospect's LinkedIn profile via web search. The goal: know their name, title, what their company does, and one specific thing to reference on the call.
- Before any call, check brain/prospects/ for existing notes on the contact. Then check Apollo MCP (apollo_contacts_search) for contact data, title, company, stage, and any prior touchpoints. Pull the prospect's LinkedIn profile via web search. The goal: know their name, title, what their company does, and one specific thing to reference on the call.
- Read and apply: skills/fanatical-prospecting/SKILL.md (prospecting discipline, call structure, mental toughness), skills/outbound-playbook/SKILL.md (call scripts, objection handling, cadence structure). Also read "docs/Sales Playbooks/sales-methodology.txt" for SPIN and Gap Selling frameworks.
- Read and apply: skills/fanatical-prospecting/SKILL.md (prospecting discipline, call structure, mental toughness), skills/outbound-playbook/SKILL.md (call scripts, objection handling, cadence structure). Also read "docs/Sales Playbooks/sales-methodology.txt" for SPIN and Gap Selling frameworks.
- Structure the call using Fanatical Prospecting framework: (a) Pattern interrupt — break their autopilot with something specific about their company. (b) Bridge — connect their situation to a relevant pain point. (c) Ask — one question that invites a conversation, not a pitch. Keep it under 30 seconds before the first question. Reference something specific from research — their company, a job posting, their ad library, recent news.
- Structure the call using Fanatical Prospecting framework: (a) Pattern interrupt — break their autopilot with something specific about their company. (b) Bridge — connect their situation to a relevant pain point. (c) Ask — one question that invites a conversation, not a pitch. Keep it under 30 seconds before the first question. Reference something specific from research — their company, a job posting, their ad library, recent news.
- If the call goes to voicemail, leave a 15-second max message: Name, company, one specific observation, callback number. Example: "Hi [Name], this is Oliver from Sprites. Noticed [specific thing]. Quick question about it — my number is 555-xxx-xxxx." Do NOT pitch on voicemail. The goal is curiosity, not a sale.
- If the call goes to voicemail, leave a 15-second max message: Name, company, one specific observation, callback number. Example: "Hi [Name], this is Oliver from Sprites. Noticed [specific thing]. Quick question about it — my number is 555-xxx-xxxx." Do NOT pitch on voicemail. The goal is curiosity, not a sale.
- Have these ready based on Objection Handling notebook data: "Not interested" → "Totally fair. Quick question before I go — [probe]." "Send me an email" → "Happy to. What specifically would be most useful for you to see?" "We already have a solution" → "Got it. Out of curiosity, what are you using? [listen, don't pitch]." "I'm busy" → "I'll be quick — 30 seconds. [bridge to pain point]."
