- After every call, immediately: (a) Update brain prospect note in brain/prospects/[Name] — [Company].md with call outcome, what was said, next steps. (b) Log to Apollo via browser if stage changed. (c) If call went well, feed Objection Handling notebook with any new objections encountered: notebooklm source add "docs/Exports/notebook-feeds/[filename].md" -n 73f909fa-1ebc-4792-aa22-d810df2d7ca0. (d) If demo booked, update brain note with #demo-booked tag and check calendar.
- After every call, immediately: (a) Update brain prospect note in brain/prospects/[Name] — [Company].md with call outcome, what was said, next steps. (b) Log to Apollo via browser if stage changed. (c) If call went well, feed Objection Handling notebook with any new objections encountered: notebooklm source add "docs/Exports/notebook-feeds/[filename].md" -n 73f909fa-1ebc-4792-aa22-d810df2d7ca0. (d) If demo booked, update brain note with #demo-booked tag and check calendar.
- Gather all relevant error context before diagnosing
- Form hypothesis and test systematically
- Check logs, stack traces, and error messages first
- Isolate the problem to smallest reproducible case
- Explain root cause, not just the fix
- After adding the source, query NotebookLM for the prospect's specific pain points, current marketing setup (agencies, in-house, tools), team size, ad channels they run (Meta, Google, both), monthly ad spend if discoverable, and any recent company news or changes. Run: notebooklm ask "[prospect company] marketing setup, pain points, team size, ad channels, ad spend" -n 6bdf40a0-e9e5-462b-bfcd-02a2985214c1
- After adding the source, query NotebookLM for the prospect's specific pain points, current marketing setup (agencies, in-house, tools), team size, ad channels they run (Meta, Google, both), monthly ad spend if discoverable, and any recent company news or changes. Run: notebooklm ask "[prospect company] marketing setup, pain points, team size, ad channels, ad spend" -n 6bdf40a0-e9e5-462b-bfcd-02a2985214c1
- Read the docs/Demo Prep/ folder for any existing files matching the prospect's name or company. Check for .docx, .pdf, .md, or .txt files. Surface any prior notes, call summaries, or research already done on this person. When building a deck, load docs/Demo Prep/deck-template.md for the 8-slide structure and format rules.
- Read the docs/Demo Prep/ folder for any existing files matching the prospect's name or company. Check for .docx, .pdf, .md, or .txt files. Surface any prior notes, call summaries, or research already done on this person. When building a deck, load docs/Demo Prep/deck-template.md for the 8-slide structure and format rules.
- Before building any cheat sheet, load ALL sales playbooks (Great Demo, SPIN, Gap Selling, JOLT, Challenger). Apply each framework's structure to the prospect's specific situation. Do not use a single framework — synthesize across all of them. The cheat sheet must show which framework maps to which discovery question and which thread.
- DEPLETED BRACKET (25-40% remaining): Reinforcement mode — heavy injection active. Checkpoint progress before any multi-step operation. Summarize what's being built before any code generation. Surface context warning before accepting complex tasks. Prepare handoff summary proactively. Recommend fresh session for heavy remaining work.
- Code over explanation - show, don't tell
- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- Run tests after implementation changes when test suite exists
- Keep changes minimal - only what's directly requested
- Avoid over-engineering and premature abstraction
- Explore multiple approaches before recommending one
- Ask clarifying questions to understand intent
- Present pros and cons for each option
- Avoid jumping to implementation until direction is clear
- Summarize key decisions made during discussion
- Start with high-level overview before details
- Use concrete examples to illustrate concepts
- Build understanding incrementally - don't overwhelm
- Check for understanding before moving to next topic
- Relate new concepts to familiar ones when possible
- FRESH BRACKET (60-100% remaining): Lean mode — minimal injection overhead. Trust recent context for implementation details. Batch operations aggressively to minimize round trips. Work in current context unless task exceeds 500 LOC. Spawn agents only for explicitly parallel work.
- Connection requests have a 300-character limit. Structure: (a) One specific observation about them or their company — NOT "I came across your profile." (b) One sentence about why connecting makes sense. (c) No pitch, no ask, no CTA. The goal is acceptance, not a meeting. Example: "Hey [Name], saw your work at [Company] on [specific thing]. Running something similar in the AI marketing space — would be great to connect." Keep it casual. No formal language.
- Connection requests have a 300-character limit. Structure: (a) One specific observation about them or their company — NOT "I came across your profile." (b) One sentence about why connecting makes sense. (c) No pitch, no ask, no CTA. The goal is acceptance, not a meeting. Example: "Hey [Name], saw your work at [Company] on [specific thing]. Running something similar in the AI marketing space — would be great to connect." Keep it casual. No formal language.
- LinkedIn is one channel in a multi-touch cadence. Typical pattern: Day 1 — email. Day 3 — LinkedIn connect. Day 5 — call. Day 7 — email follow-up. Day 10 — LinkedIn DM if connected. Never send a LinkedIn message AND an email on the same day. Space them out. (See also DUPLICATE_OUTREACH_RULE in .carl/global for hard 24-hour channel block.)
- LinkedIn is one channel in a multi-touch cadence. Typical pattern: Day 1 — email. Day 3 — LinkedIn connect. Day 5 — call. Day 7 — email follow-up. Day 10 — LinkedIn DM if connected. Never send a LinkedIn message AND an email on the same day. Space them out. (See also DUPLICATE_OUTREACH_RULE in .carl/global for hard 24-hour channel block.)
- When a LinkedIn connection responds positively: (a) Check if they exist in Apollo (apollo_contacts_search). If not, create them (apollo_contacts_create) with LinkedIn URL, name, title, company. (b) Update brain prospect note with LinkedIn interaction details. (c) If they agree to a call/demo, add to calendar and update brain note with #demo-booked tag.
- When a LinkedIn connection responds positively: (a) Check if they exist in Apollo (apollo_contacts_search). If not, create them (apollo_contacts_create) with LinkedIn URL, name, title, company. (b) Update brain prospect note with LinkedIn interaction details. (c) If they agree to a call/demo, add to calendar and update brain note with #demo-booked tag.
- After any LinkedIn outreach, update the brain prospect note with: what was sent, when, their response (if any), and next step. This prevents duplicate outreach and keeps the brain current. Also log to Apollo Activities if possible.
